<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p id="story">
      The 
      <span id="noun1"></span>
      <span id="verb1"></span>
      the
      <span id="noun2"></span>.
      <span id="question"></span>?
      The
      <span id="noun3"></span>
      replied, '
      <span id="verb2"></span>
      to the
      <span id="noun4"></span>
      <span id="question"></span>
    </p>    
    <script>
    var noun1 = prompt("A noun");
    var noun2 = prompt("A noun");
    var noun3 = prompt("A noun");
    var verb1 = prompt("A verb");
    var verb2 = prompt('A verb');
    var question = prompt('A Question');
    document.querySelector('#noun1').textContent = noun1;
    document.querySelector('#noun2').textContent = noun2;
    document.querySelector('#noun3').textContent = noun2;
    document.querySelector('#noun4').textContent = noun3;
    document.querySelector('#verb1').textContent = verb1;
    document.querySelector('#verb2').textContent = verb2;
    document.querySelector('#question').textContent = question;
    </script>
  </body>
</html>





<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Greeter</title>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="greeting">
    </div>

    <p>
        It's a pleasure having a visitor from: <span id="hometown"></span> !
    </p>

    <script>
        var visitor_name = prompt("Enter your name:");
        var welcome_message = "Welcome, " + visitor_name + "!";
        
        document.querySelector("#greeting").textContent = welcome_message;
        var town = prompt("What is your hometown?");
        document.querySelector("#hometown").textContent = town;
    </script>
</body>
</html>




<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>My First JavaScript Enabled Web Page</title>
</head>
<body>
    <p>Exercise: My First JavaScript Enabled Web Page</p>
    <p>==============================================</p>
    
    <ol>
      <li>Create a new HTML document, correctly set up with html, head, and body tags</li>
      <li>Add a script tag directly before the closing body tag.</li>
      <li>Inside of a script tag, alert visitors that your site is extremely awesome and should thus be enjoyed with caution.</li>
      <li>Prompt the user for their name</li>
      <li>Greet them by name using another alert</li>
    <ol>

    <p>In steps 4 and 5, the word alert came before the word prompt.</p>
    <p>Why did the prompt happen first? (I highly recommend you not move past this point until you can answer this
    question for yourself. Ask for help if you need to. It's okay!)</p>

    <script>
        // Displays this message in an alert window to the user.
        alert("Alert! This site is extremely awesome. Enjoy with caution!");
        // We are working from the inside of the parentheses outwards.
        // First, the prompt function asks the user for their name.
        // The user's input is then substituted, or "plugged in", where the
        // prompt function originally was.
        // Finally, the welcome message is concatenated together from three strings:
        // 1. "Greetings, "
        // 2. A string that contains the user's input from the prompt
        // 3. "!"
        alert("Greetings, " + prompt("What is your name?") + "!");
    </script>
</body>
</html>




